    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "6ff6198d81d52a37",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "6ff6198d81d52a37",
        "text": "Fuchs comes to the conclusion that the SELF system represents a special [[form]] of \"organization of 'sense-soaked' [[perception]]s\" (p. 67), which is based on the fact that the \"medium of language\" is narratively \"supercoded\" (p. 70), i.e. sociolinguistic and neurophenomenological perspectives intertwine in a special way here. We are dealing with a two-stage process of conditioned co-production, as a consequence of which the SELF re-enters itself as a doer and experiencer. First, the \"mental system\" per se always appears as a \"social interpretation of brain performance\" (p. 81). In the sense of Maturana and Varela (1987), it represents nothing else than the result of a social coordination of perceptions and behavior that has always preceded experience."
